      "content": "US labor unions have a long history dating back to the 19th century, growing significantly during the 20th century as they secured better wages, benefits, and working conditions for workers. While they once represented a large portion of the workforce, membership has declined sharply in recent decades, currently standing at roughly 10% of the private sector. Today, unions are still vital in specific industries like transportation and public sector jobs, though they face challenges in recruiting new members and adapting to the gig economy. Overall, the union movement is in a transitional phase, struggling to regain its former influence while continuing to fight for worker rights in a changing economic landscape.",
